WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.940
If the text is small on some of these slides and you

00:00:05.940 --> 00:00:08.910
want to follow along, or you want some spoilers, you

00:00:08.910 --> 00:00:11.260
can get the slides locally.

00:00:11.260 --> 00:00:14.040
I also just posted the link on my account.

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:16.940
Yeah, thanks everybody for coming.

00:00:16.940 --> 00:00:19.130
I'm going to jump right in.

00:00:19.140 --> 00:00:20.650
I'm Fig or Phil.

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:23.750
You might know me as a bad example.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:27.910
And last year when I was here, I had shipped Const

00:00:27.910 --> 00:00:29.120
ellation.

00:00:29.130 --> 00:00:33.280
And since then, I've done a few other things.

00:00:33.280 --> 00:00:40.110
This talk is about community infrastructure and specifically small scale community infrastructure

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:40.280
.

00:00:40.280 --> 00:00:42.800
And I was trying to think about how to define that scope

00:00:42.830 --> 00:00:43.160
.

00:00:43.270 --> 00:00:47.420
And I couldn't, like there's some obvious things that

00:00:47.420 --> 00:00:48.380
I wanted to say.

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:51.070
And like for the purpose of this talk, I ended up

00:00:51.070 --> 00:00:54.230
just settling on things that's kind of weird that you can

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:54.910
just do.

00:00:54.940 --> 00:00:58.000
App Proto has a lot of this, but I'm

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:02.900
just going to be talking about it in the context of small

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:04.040
scale infra.

00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:07.960
You can relay the whole firehose yourself just as like

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:09.340
a random person.

00:01:09.340 --> 00:01:12.190
And that's like kind of weird.

00:01:12.190 --> 00:01:16.090
I think Twitter had open access to a firehose early

00:01:16.090 --> 00:01:16.550
on.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:18.910
And that was like really wild.

00:01:18.910 --> 00:01:21.640
App Proto lets you run the firehose yourself in

00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:23.720
a much, much more powerful way.

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:28.460
And on a full network scale, like Blue Sky, a

00:01:28.530 --> 00:01:32.590
major social media company could use my relay for the day if

00:01:32.590 --> 00:01:33.470
they wanted.

00:01:33.470 --> 00:01:35.960
And there's a lot of reason they wouldn't.

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:38.570
But those reasons are not that it wouldn't work.

00:01:38.570 --> 00:01:40.970
It would actually like everything, you wouldn't notice a difference

00:01:40.970 --> 00:01:41.170
.

00:01:44.140 --> 00:01:46.320
You can also just index everything.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:47.690
So that's Constellation.

00:01:47.730 --> 00:01:53.810
Every single social interaction is a backlink in App Proto

00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:54.090
.

00:01:54.390 --> 00:01:57.890
And all of those go into my house, into my living

00:01:57.950 --> 00:01:58.720
room.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:01.540
And this googly-eyed Raspberry Pi takes note of them

00:02:01.540 --> 00:02:01.740
.

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:06.410
I'm going to talk a little bit about Constellation

00:02:06.410 --> 00:02:06.600
.

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:09.320
It's really simple.

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:12.260
So I made this diagram that makes it look really complicated.

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:16.720
The firehose comes in with all the posts and blocks

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.090
and likes and everything that's happening on the network called records

00:02:20.090 --> 00:02:20.250
.

00:02:20.250 --> 00:02:22.770
Constellation opens each of those up and searches through for

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:24.060
anything that looks like a link.

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:27.460
And it doesn't matter what type it is.

00:02:27.460 --> 00:02:30.710
If something looks like a link, it will take note of

00:02:30.710 --> 00:02:31.500
where it came from.

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:34.890
And then just sort of put those in buckets of backlinks

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:35.120
.

00:02:35.120 --> 00:02:37.440
So you can say, what are all the replies to this

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:38.120
post?

00:02:38.120 --> 00:02:41.400
And Constellation can tell you because it's indexed

00:02:41.400 --> 00:02:44.700
a bucket of replies to every single post that's ever happened

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:45.980
that you can just ask about.

00:02:49.980 --> 00:02:54.300
So Rudy mentioned the follower counts that are really important to everybody

00:02:54.300 --> 00:02:54.410
.

00:02:54.640 --> 00:02:57.200
And this is an example of where you need that kind of

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.840
aggregation across the network to be able to just show this

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:01.940
number on someone's profile.

00:03:01.940 --> 00:03:06.880
So that's something that you can get from Blue Sky.

00:03:07.070 --> 00:03:10.280
Their sort of like server backend has an API that can get

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:14.940
you lots of information about the profile, including doing this kind

00:03:14.940 --> 00:03:20.460
of network aggregation of everybody that follows Sharpie.

00:03:20.460 --> 00:03:25.580
You just give it their identity and you say get profile and

00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:27.120
you get an answer back.

00:03:27.120 --> 00:03:28.990
So the same thing with Constellation.

00:03:29.050 --> 00:03:32.340
You have to give it sort of one more thing, which

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:35.120
is like, where are the links coming from?

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:38.080
So in this case, we're asking about follows.

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:41.700
And within a follow record, the link to define a follow

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:43.440
is the subject of the follow.

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:46.660
And then Constellation will kind of give you exactly the

00:03:46.830 --> 00:03:49.920
same kind of information, but in a generic general purpose way

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:53.230
that's not specific to Blue Sky, works for every app

00:03:53.290 --> 00:03:53.680
, Proto app.

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:57.470
People use it.

00:03:57.570 --> 00:04:02.340
And people use it a lot more recently as well, which

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:03.440
I'll come back to in a second.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:12.540
This is all pretty low cost to run because it's running

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.680
on Raspberry Pi at my house.

00:04:15.680 --> 00:04:18.400
So something like spores.

00:04:18.400 --> 00:04:21.440
garden, when you have it show you the series of

00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:26.660
steps that one of your mushroom spores has, or whatever

00:04:26.660 --> 00:04:29.050
it is, has like gotten to you, it will reach

00:04:29.050 --> 00:04:31.680
out to my living room, Cassiopeia up there

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:33.840
, and it will tell them.

00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:39.450
There's a problem with this, which is my internet is

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:42.780
from an internet service provider that gives me a dynamic IP address

00:04:42.780 --> 00:04:42.970
.

00:04:42.970 --> 00:04:45.580
And there's also just one Raspberry Pi.

00:04:45.630 --> 00:04:49.110
And if it crashes then a lot of apps have issues.

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:59.370
So, I had a support to buy this little

00:04:59.400 --> 00:05:03.440
micro PC that runs a hot failover, also at my

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:03.670
house.

00:05:03.680 --> 00:05:10.030
And if the Raspberry Pi has any issues, then we just

00:05:10.030 --> 00:05:12.320
failover to the secondary instance.

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:14.280
So, we have like a little bit of redundancy fail

00:05:14.280 --> 00:05:15.360
over happening here.

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:19.420
I also don't actually really want to put my even dynamic

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:21.840
IP directly on the internet.

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:26.480
So, I have this little $5 a month cloud server

00:05:26.480 --> 00:05:30.010
VPS that acts as a reverse proxy, gives me some

00:05:30.190 --> 00:05:32.640
nice things, like I do TLS termination there,

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:35.670
caching and rate limiting, and then it's just the

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:39.220
upstream configuration in NGINX over tail scale to get

00:05:39.220 --> 00:05:41.680
to my house and I don't have to worry about dynamic

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:42.040
IPs.

00:05:42.040 --> 00:05:43.800
So, we're at $5 a month to do this

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:43.840
.

00:05:43.840 --> 00:05:47.550
But we also have a new single point of failure, which

00:05:47.590 --> 00:05:49.840
is that $5 a month VPS that needs to be

00:05:49.840 --> 00:05:52.340
updated and restarted and stuff from time to time.

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:54.480
So, we do the same thing.

00:05:56.960 --> 00:05:59.570
I put one on DigitalOcean and one on Vulture

00:05:59.570 --> 00:06:04.960
, so Constellation can survive an entire platform-wide

00:06:04.960 --> 00:06:06.570
outage on DigitalOcean if it goes down, as

00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:08.640
long as Vulture and DigitalOcean don't go down

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:09.200
at the same time.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:13.840
How do you load balance in front of that?

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:17.900
It's not a load balancer for reasons that if anybody

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.570
wants to talk about, we can talk about after.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:23.010
But for the moment, it's just DNS-based load

00:06:23.010 --> 00:06:27.200
balancing, which in practice with two instances works really well.

00:06:27.200 --> 00:06:31.410
DNS is pretty reliable, but I guess I would get taken

00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:32.670
down by a DNS outage.

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:36.300
And things just kind of like automatically fail over between them.

00:06:37.280 --> 00:06:39.970
So, this is up to $10 a month now for

00:06:39.970 --> 00:06:41.360
Constellation.

00:06:41.360 --> 00:06:47.950
Running at home still has challenges.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:52.990
Last summer, the fiber connection to my house was cut at

00:06:53.030 --> 00:06:57.280
the distribution box accidentally, presumably.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:01.040
And so, I was able at the time to like t

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:07.040
ether over cellular for a couple days until a tech could come

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:07.820
out to fix it.

00:07:07.820 --> 00:07:10.340
I don't think at the current scale of use that would

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:11.340
actually work.

00:07:11.850 --> 00:07:16.580
But I'm looking at maybe getting a cable secondary internet connection

00:07:16.930 --> 00:07:17.060
.

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:21.520
I had a power outage in January that was longer than

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:23.530
my battery backup UPS runtime.

00:07:23.530 --> 00:07:26.060
So, we had a one-hour downtime of Constell

00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:27.250
ation for that.

00:07:27.280 --> 00:07:32.290
But it's very cheap to do all this, and it

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:33.600
's very low-tech.

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:36.290
And the thing that I like about low-tech is that

00:07:36.290 --> 00:07:38.800
nothing really goes wrong generally.

00:07:38.800 --> 00:07:42.880
And when they do, they're usually really easy to figure

00:07:42.880 --> 00:07:44.720
out what's going on and debug.

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:46.870
And I guess just in case anybody's still worried about this

00:07:46.870 --> 00:07:50.860
, like running at my house, there's also public backups

00:07:50.860 --> 00:07:54.680
of the Constellation database that are pushed every four hours

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:56.080
to object storage.

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:59.550
You can get it yourself and restore a full copy of Const

00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:01.300
ellation to run if you want.

00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:05.460
And it also means that if something catastrophic happens at my house

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:08.060
, I can be back up in the cloud within some hours

00:08:08.060 --> 00:08:08.310
.

00:08:08.610 --> 00:08:12.320
But I don't have to pay for that in the meantime

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:13.760
other than the object storage.

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:22.060
We're going to get out of Microcosm specific

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:24.200
in a second, but I did want to just kind of

00:08:24.200 --> 00:08:27.630
follow Constellation a little further than I did last year

00:08:27.630 --> 00:08:30.260
, which is that it's only storing the links.

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:33.990
It's not storing any like record contents from Constellation

00:08:33.990 --> 00:08:34.320
.

00:08:34.320 --> 00:08:36.830
So, when you ask for all the replies to a post

00:08:37.040 --> 00:08:40.920
, you might get like this thread of many responses, but

00:08:40.920 --> 00:08:44.280
you have to go and fetch each of those individually to render

00:08:44.310 --> 00:08:45.170
a UI like this.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:50.480
And in the protocol, we have get record sync or repo

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:51.680
versions.

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:54.960
And if the PDS has that record is offline, then

00:08:54.960 --> 00:08:59.360
you might be in luck if you put your request through Sl

00:08:59.360 --> 00:09:03.760
ingshot, which is an edge record cache.

00:09:03.760 --> 00:09:06.480
It keeps a cache of the firehose and then a

00:09:06.610 --> 00:09:10.720
cache of requested identities and records from them so that you have

00:09:10.720 --> 00:09:13.440
much faster responses for get record.

00:09:13.440 --> 00:09:16.060
And if it's in the cache, then you don't

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:17.360
need to worry about availability.

00:09:17.360 --> 00:09:25.360
And you can also proxy your request Constellation through

00:09:25.360 --> 00:09:27.920
Slingshot and have it hydrate everything on this way

00:09:27.920 --> 00:09:28.240
out.

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:31.900
So, you can do one single request to get that thread

00:09:31.980 --> 00:09:34.960
UI fully hydrated on the way out.

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:38.780
Rudy mentioned like record hydration is just that one above the water

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:40.050
thing of building it up to you.

00:09:40.050 --> 00:09:42.960
And I don't want to pretend that I'm saying anything

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:47.520
otherwise, but I think this can get you pretty far.

00:09:47.870 --> 00:09:57.200
I'm going to just show

00:09:57.200 --> 00:10:01.150
these two graphs from data that I pulled yesterday from another micro

00:10:01.150 --> 00:10:04.360
cosm service called UFOs, which tracks some statistics about

00:10:04.410 --> 00:10:05.520
every lexicon that comes through the firehose.

00:10:05.520 --> 00:10:12.230
I think this one might surprise some people given how much hype

00:10:12.240 --> 00:10:14.260
there is around the atmosphere.

00:10:14.260 --> 00:10:17.680
The top of that y-axis is 15,000 unique

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:18.000
people.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:22.640
We've never broken 15,000 unique people using non-

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:24.310
blue sky apps within a week.

00:10:24.310 --> 00:10:26.400
It's small.

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.720
It's early.

00:10:28.720 --> 00:10:34.890
And like the trend from like after the conference last year for

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:37.360
most of the year was not exciting.

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:41.340
I don't actually, I didn't have time to figure

00:10:41.340 --> 00:10:43.880
out what this one spike was earlier, but I do want

00:10:44.050 --> 00:10:46.830
to just like point to that last kind of two or three

00:10:46.830 --> 00:10:49.190
months at the end there that kind of corresponded to the

00:10:49.190 --> 00:10:53.120
rise that I have in stuff using microcosm.

00:10:53.120 --> 00:10:57.250
The orange one with question marks is there because that's actually

00:10:57.250 --> 00:10:59.730
only one day of the weekly bucket.

00:10:59.730 --> 00:11:01.750
So this bucket is still rising up.

00:11:01.750 --> 00:11:04.080
And I, and I think, I think this kind of

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:04.950
more recent thing.

00:11:04.960 --> 00:11:05.200
Yeah.

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:06.400
Oh, nice.

00:11:06.400 --> 00:11:08.000
Nice.

00:11:08.010 --> 00:11:09.260
Awesome.

00:11:09.260 --> 00:11:09.700
Awesome.

00:11:09.770 --> 00:11:11.120
Yeah.

00:11:11.120 --> 00:11:18.400
These charts kind of show something interesting together, like these two

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:20.600
, which are basically the same thing versus the one on the

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:24.700
last slide, which is that even though uptake among users

00:11:24.780 --> 00:11:30.240
has been slow, uptake among developers has been steady.

00:11:30.240 --> 00:11:33.730
And I think that's why this like lag and now we

00:11:33.730 --> 00:11:34.780
're seeing the growth.

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:36.250
Like I, I think it's early.

00:11:36.250 --> 00:11:39.120
I don't think these are actually pessimistic slides.

00:11:39.120 --> 00:11:44.030
But yeah, so more than 10 weekly active users using a

00:11:44.030 --> 00:11:46.900
given lexicon or data type bucketed, we've

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.110
got like, you know, almost 80 of them now,

00:11:49.110 --> 00:11:52.540
lexicon groups that have more than 10 people using them

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:53.600
at least one time in a week.

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:57.920
Okay.

00:11:57.920 --> 00:11:59.910
I'm doing okay on time.

00:11:59.910 --> 00:12:02.240
I think so I'm going to say this part.

00:12:02.240 --> 00:12:06.480
I said I would talk about economics.

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:09.310
It's kind of boring, but end of 2025, I

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:13.540
pulled some numbers and I was getting around $200 after fees

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:19.680
from people sponsoring me on GitHub and Ko-Fi or coffee

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:22.680
or however you say it, which with some of the more

00:12:22.990 --> 00:12:26.240
expensive cloud servers for Slingshot and stuff netted me

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:27.360
about $33 a month.

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:29.280
I'm getting rich.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:35.440
I've gotten some grants that have helped.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:41.260
Shout out Haifa, who gave me a really generous donation

00:12:41.260 --> 00:12:42.220
recently.

00:12:42.220 --> 00:12:45.420
And UpCloud sponsored a lot of the PLC stuff I

00:12:45.420 --> 00:12:47.120
was doing for hosting.

00:12:47.120 --> 00:12:53.590
I'm going to be building Hubble soon, which has come

00:12:53.590 --> 00:12:57.640
with a grant from Blue Sky and will come with operating expenses

00:12:57.640 --> 00:12:58.880
for the year I have to run it.

00:12:58.880 --> 00:13:01.840
I don't know how much it's going to cost yet

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:03.740
, because I haven't built it.

00:13:03.740 --> 00:13:08.720
But in 2024, running the close comparable existing thing wasn't

00:13:09.030 --> 00:13:09.280
cheap.

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:15.560
Since I mentioned relays, so we had that $15

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:18.220
3 a month in 2024.

00:13:18.310 --> 00:13:22.220
Last year at the conference, there was somebody trying to run

00:13:22.220 --> 00:13:23.830
$2 million to run a relay.

00:13:23.870 --> 00:13:25.760
We can skip past that.

00:13:27.040 --> 00:13:29.730
Future ran it on a Raspberry Pi after that because non-

00:13:29.730 --> 00:13:32.720
archival relays, so not what I'm doing with

00:13:32.720 --> 00:13:34.460
Hubble, are cheap.

00:13:34.460 --> 00:13:37.760
I got one up in the cloud for $30 a month

00:13:37.760 --> 00:13:39.760
the month after that.

00:13:39.910 --> 00:13:42.830
Got it down to $18 on a different provider.

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:45.490
Brian did it for $34 a month and wrote it up

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:46.560
in a nice post.

00:13:46.560 --> 00:13:51.140
And last month, I got one working on a under $

00:13:51.170 --> 00:13:52.820
5 a month VPS.

00:13:53.210 --> 00:14:01.370
The network is growing, but it

00:14:01.370 --> 00:14:08.000
's weird that you can just run infra pretty affordably.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:12.310
These are some other ways I think I might be able to

00:14:12.310 --> 00:14:13.810
make money and some ideas.

00:14:13.810 --> 00:14:16.470
But this is actually what I want to get to, which

00:14:16.470 --> 00:14:20.110
is, I don't know, why do people do weird

00:14:20.240 --> 00:14:22.330
things in AppProto?

00:14:22.330 --> 00:14:28.000
I didn't think my answers alone would be very interesting.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:34.540
I reached out to 10 people that are running relays or

