APIs or other things on a very small scale.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.480
And I got 10 responses back.

00:14:40.480 --> 00:14:42.910
Shout out to all those people, some in this room.

00:14:42.910 --> 00:14:43.600
Thank you.

00:14:43.600 --> 00:14:47.890
And yeah, I realized that I had never asked any of

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:50.350
them why they do it, and I didn't really know

00:14:50.390 --> 00:14:50.640
.

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:56.800
So I tried to consolidate some of those answers here.

00:14:56.800 --> 00:15:01.110
A lot of people do it for fun, to learn things

00:15:01.110 --> 00:15:05.280
, or they needed something for themselves and decided to open it

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:07.600
up, or to show what's possible.

00:15:07.600 --> 00:15:09.040
These were like recurring themes.

00:15:09.040 --> 00:15:18.320
I think

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:21.350
some of the real idealism came out in these.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:23.870
I think this is the best chance we've had in a

00:15:23.870 --> 00:15:27.440
long time to make this social internet more independent for the few

00:15:27.570 --> 00:15:29.100
mostly evil big tech companies.

00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:34.240
I asked people how they pay for it.

00:15:34.240 --> 00:15:39.350
Almost 100% out of pocket at this kind of like small

00:15:39.350 --> 00:15:41.130
scale, which I guess makes sense.

00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:43.680
But people do that by running things cheap.

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:48.390
Some people, one person did it out of pocket because they

00:15:48.390 --> 00:15:53.310
can't accept money or grants due to work or other reasons

00:15:53.310 --> 00:15:53.440
.

00:15:55.360 --> 00:16:00.110
GitHub and CoFi support to do this kind of stuff is

00:16:00.170 --> 00:16:04.270
a huge recurring theme across everybody that answered this.

00:16:04.270 --> 00:16:07.160
Small grants and in some cases people are able to run things

00:16:07.330 --> 00:16:10.640
that fit within free offerings from services.

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:24.690
So someone said they're blessed to have enough GitHub and Co

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:26.370
Fi donations to cover costs.

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:31.840
Yeah, small grants and then out of pocket and then supported

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:31.840
.

00:16:31.840 --> 00:16:36.020
Again, if you want to read more of these, you

00:16:36.020 --> 00:16:37.760
can get the slides.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:45.060
I asked what people thought about sort of like small indie infrastructure

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:47.980
in the long term, keeping it going or like what they

00:16:47.980 --> 00:16:50.980
think about when they think about winding it down when maybe people

00:16:51.040 --> 00:16:51.680
start using it.

00:16:51.680 --> 00:16:56.720
So it either has to become too expensive or I get bored

00:16:56.720 --> 00:16:57.520
of posting my infra.

00:16:57.520 --> 00:16:59.200
Neither are true at the moment.

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:03.040
Or I think if things go well, people like you and

00:17:03.070 --> 00:17:06.050
Bailey and others will be able to make a living providing hosting

00:17:06.050 --> 00:17:06.210
.

00:17:06.210 --> 00:17:06.960
We can dream.

00:17:09.200 --> 00:17:12.100
Yeah, unless things get massively expensive, then people kind of

00:17:12.100 --> 00:17:13.400
just want to keep it online.

00:17:13.440 --> 00:17:18.860
Not everybody had optimistic takes here.

00:17:18.880 --> 00:17:22.880
Keep stuff running because I have to and it has become somewhat

00:17:22.880 --> 00:17:25.120
load-bearing for the ecosystem, was a response.

00:17:25.120 --> 00:17:32.690
But people also expressed a lot of thought in how they were

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:36.120
thinking about how people might get off of their services if they

00:17:36.120 --> 00:17:36.880
had to wind it down.

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:41.030
So providing like open source codes that people can run it themselves

00:17:41.030 --> 00:17:43.160
and it's cheap because it has to be cheap because these

00:17:43.160 --> 00:17:46.730
are small-scale operators and trying to make those migration paths

00:17:46.730 --> 00:17:47.200
exist.

00:17:47.210 --> 00:17:54.690
Yeah, I really don't see how developers ever break even

00:17:54.740 --> 00:17:57.450
or make money off projects like this and the company is too

00:17:57.450 --> 00:18:01.040
inconsistent with who it chooses to fund or how often it funds

00:18:01.130 --> 00:18:01.280
them.

00:18:02.240 --> 00:18:03.200
It was a thought.

00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:10.480
I asked what people thought the future of social infrastructure will look

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:10.690
like.

00:18:10.720 --> 00:18:16.980
Medium and large-scale community PDSs like Black Sky

00:18:16.980 --> 00:18:18.160
, North Sky, Euro Sky.

00:18:18.160 --> 00:18:21.860
I would include Bridgie in here, but that came up

00:18:21.860 --> 00:18:22.480
a lot.

00:18:22.480 --> 00:18:25.540
I think people really do see that as the way it's

00:18:25.540 --> 00:18:25.920
going to go.

00:18:25.920 --> 00:18:29.120
Personally, I think we're also going to see like a

00:18:29.120 --> 00:18:34.270
lot more of people like these dozen or so like independent tiny

00:18:34.310 --> 00:18:36.240
small-scale operators as well.

00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:41.920
Maybe it'll be more centralized, more mindless.

00:18:41.920 --> 00:18:42.640
Maybe I'll be wrong.

00:18:42.640 --> 00:18:42.880
Yeah.

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:49.680
How could communities or companies better support came up a little bit

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:49.840
.

00:18:49.840 --> 00:18:54.850
Some of the coolest things to run that maybe is only at

00:18:54.850 --> 00:18:58.560
a prototype stage needs a lot of resources and more than you

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:00.870
might be able to do at like a very small-scale

00:19:00.870 --> 00:19:02.320
IndieInfra operator.

00:19:02.320 --> 00:19:04.480
And so that came up a few times.

00:19:04.480 --> 00:19:06.470
Like, is there a way we can kind of pool community

00:19:06.470 --> 00:19:11.040
resources to provide that sort of like available infrastructure to try some

00:19:11.170 --> 00:19:15.600
experiments that would be driven on that sort of like smaller individual

00:19:15.600 --> 00:19:15.920
basis?

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:22.340
When I was getting through these, I also realized that like

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:26.010
I have a bunch of people supporting me on GitHub and Ko

00:19:26.010 --> 00:19:29.760
Fi and I've never really like directly asked any of them

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:33.150
like, "Why do you support me?" So I got

00:19:33.150 --> 00:19:38.560
eight people to reply to some questions that I sent to people

00:19:38.560 --> 00:19:42.570
who are supporting folks running small-scale IndieInf

00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:42.880
ra.

00:19:46.160 --> 00:19:47.360
These are in the reverse order.

00:19:47.360 --> 00:19:51.440
So what those people, so supporters of small-scale Ind

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:54.690
ieInfra think that the future of social infrastructure will

00:19:54.690 --> 00:19:57.360
look like more big companies involved in AppProto.

00:19:57.360 --> 00:19:58.560
This is all like AppProto.

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:02.860
A mix of software as a service and public services.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:06.150
I'm pretty hopeful about that one and optimistic.

00:20:06.370 --> 00:20:10.930
We have some examples that people pointed to like Debian,

00:20:10.930 --> 00:20:13.580
Wikimedia, a couple others that I forgot to put

00:20:13.580 --> 00:20:14.080
on here.

00:20:14.080 --> 00:20:20.140
And yeah, people don't think there will be a future

00:20:20.230 --> 00:20:22.440
where social Infra isn't free for the public to use

00:20:22.440 --> 00:20:22.580
.

00:20:22.580 --> 00:20:26.580
I think that's not disproven so far by App

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:27.840
Proto.

00:20:27.840 --> 00:20:31.650
And yeah, shout out to QuickSlice, where you

00:20:31.650 --> 00:20:34.840
can run your own backend, self-host, pull in

00:20:34.850 --> 00:20:36.850
just what you need from the big network, if that's

00:20:36.850 --> 00:20:37.760
what you're trying to do.

00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:45.900
Laptops with batteries, with swelling batteries

00:20:45.900 --> 00:20:48.400
, yet handle 1000+ concurrent users just fine.

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:51.350
I think this came from like the theme of we can just

00:20:51.350 --> 00:20:55.920
make things more cheap by putting effort into making them efficient,

00:20:55.920 --> 00:20:58.330
as we've seen by small-scale operators in AppPr

00:20:58.330 --> 00:20:58.740
oto.

00:21:06.560 --> 00:21:11.520
So from the funders' perspective, supporting small-scale

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:14.150
people, thinking about the future and winding it down, I

00:21:14.150 --> 00:21:15.280
really like this one.

00:21:15.280 --> 00:21:16.900
Not on my watch.

00:21:17.010 --> 00:21:22.870
As it expands, financial sustainability might become more challenging, but

00:21:22.870 --> 00:21:25.590
due to the immense benefits it provides, I'm optimistic that

00:21:25.600 --> 00:21:26.720
solutions can be found.

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:28.240
I kind of feel this way too.

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:33.210
I think as the whole network grows, the resources of everybody

00:21:33.210 --> 00:21:35.900
to support small-scale things also grows.

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:42.170
Probably there will be some business models or some donation-based

00:21:42.170 --> 00:21:44.560
nonprofits that can support what's needed in the long term.

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:46.560
But yeah.

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:51.250
And some people feel comfortable donating right now, but don't

00:21:51.250 --> 00:21:53.550
know how long that will be the case for themselves or others

00:21:53.550 --> 00:21:53.760
.

00:21:53.760 --> 00:21:57.710
So again, mixed, it's not all like pure optimism

00:21:57.710 --> 00:21:59.840
around this, but I think everybody is like kind of,

00:21:59.880 --> 00:22:02.980
I would say, guarded optimism or cautious for the most part

00:22:02.980 --> 00:22:03.200
.

00:22:03.310 --> 00:22:07.070
Open-sourced.

00:22:07.070 --> 00:22:11.370
And I think like we talk about the permissionlessness of App

00:22:11.370 --> 00:22:12.850
Proto a lot as well.

00:22:12.850 --> 00:22:16.550
And yeah, what ends up critical will be replaced if needed

00:22:16.550 --> 00:22:16.780
.

00:22:16.780 --> 00:22:20.530
Um, because this is a really small-scale operations and

00:22:20.820 --> 00:22:23.280
you can just replace it.

00:22:23.280 --> 00:22:26.920
I'm trying really hard not to say you can just do

00:22:26.930 --> 00:22:27.440
things.

00:22:27.560 --> 00:22:36.940
Why do people support

00:22:36.990 --> 00:22:37.670
public infra?

00:22:37.700 --> 00:22:41.470
The biggest one was that they were in a position to be

00:22:41.470 --> 00:22:42.250
able to do it.

00:22:42.370 --> 00:22:44.800
Um, they want to see the atmosphere succeed, and they

00:22:44.800 --> 00:22:47.450
think that very small-scale operators are a part of that

00:22:47.450 --> 00:22:47.680
.

00:22:47.890 --> 00:22:50.890
Um, the option to self-host came up a lot

00:22:50.890 --> 00:22:51.060
.

00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:53.280
Um, just the fact that you can do that for these

00:22:53.320 --> 00:22:56.770
different components like PDS, of course, but not just

00:22:56.770 --> 00:22:57.540
the PDS.

00:22:57.540 --> 00:23:02.000
Um, it provides that kind of assurance that people want.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:06.310
Um, this one was cool.

00:23:06.320 --> 00:23:08.910
Like, I might not be using most of the services I

00:23:08.920 --> 00:23:11.460
sponsor for, but I know others are and may not be

00:23:11.460 --> 00:23:12.880
able to sponsor it themselves.

00:23:12.880 --> 00:23:15.560
Like, I would say even more than the people running,

00:23:15.560 --> 00:23:19.370
uh, infrastructure, the responses from people funding it were like

00:23:19.630 --> 00:23:23.870
really this kind of, uh, beautiful, um, community

00:23:23.870 --> 00:23:27.760
-oriented sentiments around just, like, supporting the ecosystem.

00:23:28.030 --> 00:23:34.240
Um, this came up a lot.

00:23:34.240 --> 00:23:36.820
It's important to support maintainers of projects I build on

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:41.120
, especially when those projects aren't backed by huge companies.

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:45.190
Uh, yeah, I would say more than that, more

00:23:45.190 --> 00:23:45.980
of that.

00:23:46.040 --> 00:23:50.890
Um, and I'm going to close it on this quote

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:54.130
, which I liked, uh, more community-led than

00:23:54.130 --> 00:23:55.580
big business-led.

00:23:55.580 --> 00:23:58.310
I think this is like a high bar to aim for,

00:23:58.310 --> 00:24:02.320
but, um, I, I think we can try.

00:24:17.440 --> 00:24:19.840
Do you want to use "we can just try" as

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:21.040
an alternate?

00:24:21.040 --> 00:24:23.780
Uh, we have a couple minutes before lunch.

00:24:23.810 --> 00:24:26.720
Does anyone have a question for fake?

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:32.700
Um, with Constellation, what was the weirdest thing

00:24:32.700 --> 00:24:36.000
somebody did about it?

00:24:36.000 --> 00:24:36.880
Oh, gosh.

00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:39.530
I think I know the answer, but I'm not sure

00:24:39.530 --> 00:24:39.600
.

00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:43.840
So, the question was, what's the weirdest thing somebody

00:24:43.840 --> 00:24:45.020
has done with Constellation?

00:24:45.040 --> 00:24:48.310
Um, I should have prepared something for this, because people

00:24:48.310 --> 00:24:51.140
have done some really weird things with Constellation.

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:54.580
Um, I really love the kind of experiments people do,

00:24:54.580 --> 00:24:56.800
like Spore's Garden was neat.

00:24:56.800 --> 00:25:00.430
Um, I think one of the just surprising ones that other

00:25:00.430 --> 00:25:05.730
people think of was Bailey's, uh, hooked up his

00:25:05.730 --> 00:25:08.960
, uh, badge with the e-ink screen on it

00:25:08.960 --> 00:25:12.820
to both show the QR code for meet me, you and

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:16.020
me at, um, but then Bailey presses another button,

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:19.120
and it shows all the people that Bailey's connected with,

00:25:19.120 --> 00:25:21.940
and it queries that through Constellation, uh, and

00:25:21.940 --> 00:25:23.730
like, yeah, wild.

00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:25.570
So, but I want to hear what you thought was the

00:25:25.570 --> 00:25:25.920
weirdest.

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:32.520
I'm remembering when Aviva and I were doing Deck V

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:35.040
ulture and figuring out, okay, no, we can do

00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:36.000
Scryful URIs.

00:25:36.000 --> 00:25:37.640
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:25:37.810 --> 00:25:41.730
People, people often say, hey, you should also index

00:25:41.730 --> 00:25:43.580
URLs, not just at URIs.

00:25:43.580 --> 00:25:47.460
And Constellation has, from day one, it index

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:49.960
es anything that looks like a, a did, or an

00:25:49.970 --> 00:25:52.640
at URI, or any URI that parses like

00:25:52.640 --> 00:25:53.280
a URI.

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:56.060
So, um, if you want to see all the posts

00:25:56.060 --> 00:25:58.400
to your leaflet that are shared on Blue Sky as,

00:25:58.400 --> 00:26:00.400
like, link embeds, you can do that.

00:26:00.420 --> 00:26:03.490
And it also means you can hack the system by, uh

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:06.700
, putting, like, your own URI scheme, um

00:26:06.700 --> 00:26:09.100
, that you invent, and just, like, create links

00:26:09.100 --> 00:26:11.530
that aren't real links, but Constellation aggregates

00:26:11.650 --> 00:26:12.890
them for you, so then you can query it.

00:26:12.890 --> 00:26:14.720
You can do, kind of, like, arbitrary, uh

00:26:14.720 --> 00:26:18.430
, group, grouping and aggregation with Constellation that

00:26:18.440 --> 00:26:18.920
way.

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:20.880
Yeah, that's a good one.

00:26:20.880 --> 00:26:23.190
Any more questions?

00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:28.360
I'm just going to add one more thing on the end

00:26:28.370 --> 00:26:31.530
of that, which is, sometimes, um, people use

00:26:31.790 --> 00:26:36.690
Constellation in ways that aren't scalable, uh,

00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:40.610
like, trying to use it as a leaderboard, um

00:26:40.610 --> 00:26:45.630
, by having every score link to a URL, and then

00:26:45.990 --> 00:26:48.070
doing a lot of client-side filtering, and I think

00:26:48.070 --> 00:26:49.190
that's awesome.

00:26:49.190 --> 00:26:51.840
It won't scale forever, but if you're ever wondering

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:53.900
, like, is it okay if I can use Constell

00:26:53.900 --> 00:26:56.860
ation for this, um, it's indexing everything that

00:26:56.990 --> 00:26:58.620
happens on Blue Sky, so it can handle it.

00:26:58.620 --> 00:27:01.460
Like, whatever you're thinking about throwing at it, uh

00:27:01.570 --> 00:27:02.640
, yeah, just go for it.

00:27:02.640 --> 00:27:05.480
Amazing.

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:10.320
Thank you so much.
